flowRoot.flowPara: We calculate a preliminary series of best-possible lifetables for the United States from 1959 to 2004, defined on the basis of the age-specific aggregate of the lowest observed age-cause specific death rates among the 50 states and the District of Columbia.

The resulting highest-possible life expectancy shows a gradual increasing trend over the period, on average 1.9 and 2.2 years higher than the highest state life expectancy in each year for males and females, respectively.

The US low-morality lifetable is a useful gauge of future mortality trends. We compare state mortality patterns to benchmark life expectancy to quantify the potential for immediately acheivable improvement.

flowRoot.flowPara: All death count data come from restricted NCHS mortality microdata files. Single-age population denominators and complete state lifetables come from a beta version of the U.S. States project of the HMD. Death counts by causes of death are first grouped into 11 large cause groups and then converted to fractions in abridged age groups.

Fractions are then multiplied into single-age all-cause death rates to produce a first estimate of single-age cause-specific death rates. In order to eliminate stochastic zeros, cause-specific schedules are then smoothed over age and time using the method proposed by Camarda (2012), and then constrained to sum to the independently-smoothed all-cause mortality rates for each state.
We then produce the minimum mortality rate schedule by summing the lowest-observed cause-specific rates within each age and sex:

The difference between each state and the benchmark life expectancy of each year is then decomposed by age and cause using the generic decomposition method proposed by Horiuchi et. al. (2008).

flowRoot.flowPara: Low mortality benchmark life expectancy displays a linear trend over the period studied, much more linear than any of the state trends or the national trend. During times of stagnation (1960s) and accelerated improvement (1970s), the benchmark mortality improved at roughly the same steady rate. This benchmark shows us the improvements that can be acheived now, without any technological advancements. Perhaps the linear trend can be used to temper or guide mortality projections as well.

flowRoot.flowPara: Low mortality benchmark life expectancy lends itself to comparison with international record life expectancy. At least two papers being presented in this PAA use record life expectancy in an instrumental way to guide mortality projections. We speculate that some version of this benchmark trend could serve a similar auxiliary role in projections. See e.g.,
A. Medford 37-1 (today at 10:15): "Best Practice Life Expectancy and Extreme Value Theory"
M. Pescariu & V. Canudas-Romo 37-2 (today at 10:15): "The Double-Gap Life Expectancy Forecasting Model"

flowRoot.flowPara: Clearly this procedure is not scale- invariant: If we were to repeat the same exercise for US counties rather than states, it would produce a higher benchmark life expectancy, and likewise if we increase the number of causes. In this way we can arbitarily push the value higher or lower. For this reason, we are going to try modeling select quantiles from a latent distribution of rates. (hat tip to Jutta Gampe)

flowRoot.flowPara: This decomposition is quite different from results you'd get from cause-deletion: no causes are deleted here, we're just comparing with the best-observed rates in each cause. If the lowest death rate for a given cause is still high there may or may not be geographic variation.

flowRoot.flowPara: This display gives more visual weight to the largest cause-contributions for those causes that have the greatest state heterogeneity in terms of impacts on e(0). Attention is drawn to cerebrovascular diseases in the 1960s, and geographic patterns in cardiovascular improvements. Remember, we're always comparing with a moving target: the benchmark trend is kind of like life expectancy inflation.

Nor do we see much from those causes with high absolute impact but little between-state variation. To pop out on these maps there needs to be at least one state that is better than all the rest, and the poorly-performing states need to be doing quite bad.

flowRoot.flowPara: Data until 2013 are coming soon.
There were countervailing
state trends in the 1960s
for both males and females.
LMB improved steadily in the 1960s, even as national life expectancy stagnated.

Cardiovascular disease is unsurprisingly the cause of death that comes into sharpest relief using this decomposition method: It is a major killer, but the between-state spread is also very high. Were we to experience the hypothetical perfect diffusion of "best practices" this would close much of the gap with the low mortality benchmark.
Don't worry, the next iteration will break down the 'other' category!
For females low mortality benchmark life expectancy has increased a fairly steady 1.5 years per decade, slightly faster than national life expectancy.

The gap is decreasing with record state life expectancy, and the gap with national life expectancy has been steady in recent decades. At this rate, national life expectancy tends to catch up in around 30 years
The 2004 LMB was about 0.6 years less than Japanese life expectancy in the same year.
Low mortality benchmark life expectancy has increased a fairly steady 1.8 years per decade, slightly faster than national life expectancy.

The trend in LMB is currently rising faster than the trend in record state life expectancy. Both lines lend themselves to linear extrapolation, but they would diverge greatly if you were to do this. National life expectancy seems to keep pace with LMB more than with record state life expectancy.
The 2004 male LMB value was 1.4 years higher than Japanese male life expectancy in the same year.
